00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:43.439
of hallucinations especially high in the context of healthcare?

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:52.800
So when I embark on a project, so I don't think I've actually explained what I do very well. So

00:21:52.800 --> 00:21:56.800
let me set the stage of what my team does, and then I'll try to answer the question.

00:21:57.359 --> 00:22:05.199
So I have responsibilities for two domains. I have AI platforms, which today are not

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:11.280
products, our enterprise data lake, and then some other random technology. And then I also have a

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:15.920
delivery team, which is focused on generative AI and traditional ML stuff. So I kind of get to do

00:22:15.920 --> 00:22:23.199
both roles. So over the past year or so, we've really refined the way in which we do our

00:22:23.199 --> 00:22:28.239
delivery teams. And I think that's a big part of what I do. And I think that's one of the

00:22:28.319 --> 00:22:35.920
get to do both roles. So over the past year or so, we've really refined the way in which a project

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:41.839
comes into the queue and we execute it. Because what I've discovered is there's unlimited demand,

00:22:41.839 --> 00:22:45.760
like there's unlimited demand for build a gen AI thing that does something useful.

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:51.199
And so when you have that problem, you have to get really efficient on execution. And then you

00:22:51.199 --> 00:22:54.479
have to get really good at, how do you scope the problem so the people are happy, right?

00:22:55.040 --> 00:23:00.319
A bad project is one that takes six months and you're chasing hallucinations and you never get

00:23:00.319 --> 00:23:04.400
to the finish line. A good project is one where there's clear expectations, you can deliver it

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:09.520
quickly and stuff like that. So to this question of hallucinations, how do you deal with it?

00:23:09.520 --> 00:23:16.079
When I talk with people about building a gen AI workflow or solution or whatever, I say that this

00:23:16.079 --> 00:23:23.520
is an intrinsic part of the solution. You can't box it out. It's a feature of the LLMs. You will

00:23:23.520 --> 00:23:29.760
be unable to physically remove hallucinations from it. Now you can minimize them, right? And

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:34.719
that's what the goal is, is you built a solution that minimizes that problem, but you need to have

00:23:34.719 --> 00:23:41.599
a solution that's resilient to the hallucinations. And so when you frame it that way, it kind of gets

00:23:41.599 --> 00:23:47.599
people's minds turning in a different direction. So you're like, okay, we need this secondary

00:23:47.599 --> 00:23:54.000
verification system. That could be a human in the loop thing, or maybe what it generates,

00:23:54.000 --> 00:24:01.439
if it's wrong, it's not that big a deal. If you have a question and answer chat bot or something

00:24:01.439 --> 00:24:07.599
like that, and it's informing you on the HR procedures or what your benefits are or something

00:24:07.599 --> 00:24:11.839
like that, the risks of the hallucination there are probably lower than if it's like,

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:17.520
I just messed up something in the bioreactor, what do I do next, right? So same technology,

00:24:17.520 --> 00:24:23.280
but the risks of it being wrong are different. But there's other ways you can do secondary

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:32.239
verification. So maybe you have the solution extracts information, and you can verify with

00:24:32.239 --> 00:24:39.520
independent information. So when you do that, yeah, the model might hallucinate, but it'll at

00:24:39.520 --> 00:24:44.959
least focus you in on the thing that it hallucinated on. So if the data matched 90% of

00:24:44.959 --> 00:24:49.920
what was in a source system, and 10% is wrong, well, now you're inspecting 10%, you're not

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:56.880
inspecting 90%. So I think framing it that way has been very effective for us. And just like

00:24:57.520 --> 00:25:03.199
attacking the fallibility head on, just not hiding it and then coming up with really good

00:25:03.199 --> 00:25:10.640
ways to mitigate it as part of the solution. Awesome. Thank you. I have a question here in

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:15.760
Slido that's getting lots of updates. That's from David Kegley. David, are you available to

