00:25:37.359 --> 00:25:42.000
like sort of a leading part of this question is, do containers play a role in any of that?

00:25:46.719 --> 00:25:53.280
So when I think of repeatable solutions, I'm thinking in the context of like

00:25:54.160 --> 00:25:58.079
a chatbot, right? Like let's say you want to build a chatbot on documents.

00:25:58.959 --> 00:26:02.640
How do you like, what's the code to do that? So I think of those as, when I say

00:26:03.199 --> 00:26:08.319
repeatable, I mean like repeatable design patterns. So I think of them in terms of like code.

00:26:09.599 --> 00:26:13.920
And I think that there's this question of, there's some of these frameworks that exist now

00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:20.079
to help make this better. So LangChain is one of the most popular ones. There's also something

00:26:20.079 --> 00:26:25.199
called Llama Index. And then, you know, you're starting to see that the big research labs like

00:26:25.199 --> 00:26:29.199
OpenAI are starting to embed some of those capabilities within their SDK.

00:26:30.800 --> 00:26:37.920
To me, the jury's still out on a specific framework. We do use LangChain, but specifically,

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:41.520
we use their LangChain expression language because it's supposed to be more robust.

00:26:42.239 --> 00:26:48.719
I think that, I'm not sure yet if there's a mature framework we'll go all in on with that,

00:26:48.719 --> 00:26:55.280
but I don't really think of it like a container problem. It's really more the amount of code you

00:26:55.280 --> 00:27:00.239
need to write to build one of these solutions is actually pretty low. And something like Posit

00:27:00.239 --> 00:27:08.319
Connect product plug works really well for this. So imagine you're building some chatbot that you

00:27:08.319 --> 00:27:14.000
want other people to use. Sure, you could use Streamlit, but you could also do it in Shiny,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:19.040
like Shiny for R, and you could deploy it to Posit Connect and it could achieve the exact

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:27.359
same thing as that. So I try not to get, I operate from a perspective of simplicity. So

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:33.280
if I can do it with no packages, that's better than doing it with something else. Like you got

00:27:33.280 --> 00:27:38.560
to get something for adding complexity. And to me, adding the complexity of container and

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:43.599
container management has not yet made sense for what we're doing.

00:27:46.479 --> 00:27:51.680
Awesome, thank you. I think that this is a great place to sort of just like ask how you

00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:57.119
are using Connect. Like how does Connect play into the problems that you solve or that you're

