Sure. Yeah, thanks for hopping on here. This is a great talk. So yeah, my question is, how do you

00:30:53.119 --> 00:31:04.640
talk to stakeholders or management slash VPs if they have some idea or they want to use some new

00:31:05.599 --> 00:31:13.439
AI thing that they saw on some business project, but the data required for that project is not

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:21.680
available slash governed slash cleaned up? I've seen cases where people want to skip

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:28.719
straight from the idea on the PowerPoint slide to the finished AI product without understanding

00:31:29.680 --> 00:31:31.680
the requirements of the data.

00:31:34.479 --> 00:31:46.719
So, okay. Number one, you, the person dealing with this, need to have enough knowledge of how

00:31:46.719 --> 00:31:50.959
these tools work to be able to answer it effectively. I think that there is a prerequisite

00:31:50.959 --> 00:31:56.000
that you understand what is and is not possible with the technology, and that requires you to

00:31:56.959 --> 00:32:03.359
have tried and used it in a variety of different ways. So, like, I guess my message to folks is

00:32:03.359 --> 00:32:07.680
try to use this stuff, get a feel for how it works, what it's good and bad at,

00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:11.040
and then it'll more prepare you for these types of discussions.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:18.719
But I think the data, so the way I always frame this is, again, I spend a lot of time trying to

00:32:18.719 --> 00:32:24.479
explain AI and the way it can be applied, and the way I do it is there's inputs and outputs,

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:32.079
and typically I say if you can give the model the adequate context, it can probably answer

00:32:32.079 --> 00:32:37.040
the question, right? If you can just figure out how to get the information in some engineered

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:43.280
solution, generally it works pretty well. The problem is a lot of business process is not

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:47.280
written down. There's a lot of context that may not be in the database, right? Like, there's a

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:52.400
number, but a lot of times there's the context behind the number, and the model is incapable

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:58.719
of knowing that. So, if you kind of get them thinking about, okay, how do we frame this in

00:32:58.719 --> 00:33:04.719
a way where it can actually understand the bigger picture, and maybe that's possible,

00:33:04.719 --> 00:33:10.880
maybe it's not. But a lot of times what I do is I don't try to, like, push them off. I'll try to

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:16.239
try to deeply understand what they're trying to achieve, and there may be a smaller component

00:33:16.239 --> 00:33:20.319
you can solve with this. Maybe you don't solve the whole process. Maybe you only solve

00:33:20.319 --> 00:33:25.920
one piece, and then that actually helps you get, like, build momentum because it'll be faster to

00:33:25.920 --> 00:33:30.719
build, and then you'll have evidence that it works, right? And so, I think I try to scope them down

00:33:30.719 --> 00:33:36.079
smaller, and then you get that critical mass that can expand it, and then you attack that problem

00:33:36.719 --> 00:33:44.400
later. But, I mean, it is a legit problem. It happens a lot, but yeah, that's pretty much what I do.

