00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:12.879
between a head of AI and a leader principal data scientist? Some context for this is,

00:34:12.879 --> 00:34:17.679
I often tell my non-data scientist friends who are talking about AI that, for example,

00:34:17.679 --> 00:34:24.560
linear regression is a form of AI. When I think of a leader principal data scientist, they are

00:34:25.679 --> 00:34:32.560
managing multiple data scientists who are doing their own data science projects. And so, I guess

00:34:32.560 --> 00:34:41.679
an update to my question is, are all data science teams now essentially AI teams that are also

00:34:42.639 --> 00:34:50.239
adding generative AI projects to their portfolio? Let me know if that makes sense or not.

00:34:50.239 --> 00:34:53.840
No, this is a great question. This is actually something I wrote down before the talk,

00:34:54.479 --> 00:35:04.239
what's happening to data science. And when I look at, so my team, my team are data scientists,

00:35:04.239 --> 00:35:10.239
historically trained, classically trained, you know, regression, all that stuff. And now they're

00:35:10.239 --> 00:35:17.360
very effectively running gen AI projects. And the way I look at it is, this is like a tool in the

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:23.760
tool belt. Like AI is not, while it's new and shiny and everyone wants to get into it, data

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:29.280
scientists are uniquely positioned to be effective at this. The difference between a data scientist

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:36.239
that does shiny apps and a gen AI developer that builds AI workflows is an LLM call. The way you

00:35:36.239 --> 00:35:42.159
frame the problem is the same. You have a business problem. You're trying to figure out how to frame

00:35:42.159 --> 00:35:47.280
it and execute a series of steps to generate a desired output. Before you had shiny apps, maybe

00:35:47.280 --> 00:35:52.399
have an algorithm. Now we have an LLM to kind of stick in there, but all of the other things around

00:35:52.399 --> 00:35:58.639
it are the same. So, I think that AI teams or excuse me, data science teams should add this

00:35:58.639 --> 00:36:06.879
as a tool in the toolkit. Will all data science teams turn into AI teams? Maybe, potentially. I

00:36:06.879 --> 00:36:14.639
think that it's, if you don't and someone does this, that will be bad. I think if you push off

00:36:14.639 --> 00:36:22.479
AI as a data science team, you're at risk of being marginalized because the capabilities of the models

00:36:22.479 --> 00:36:30.000
and the tooling is increasing. And so, what do we do when the tool can do many of the things that

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:35.679
we can do, right? You don't want to be stuck as the manual verification step. You want to be

00:36:35.679 --> 00:36:40.159
building the tools because you know what the model should be doing, right? So, I think you bring a lot

00:36:40.159 --> 00:36:46.080
to the table as a data scientist in that world. The difference between a head of AI and a principal

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:53.600
data scientist, to me, they're fundamentally different. Principal data scientist is a lead.

00:36:53.600 --> 00:36:57.520
They're a tech lead. They're a person that understands the landscape of technology.

00:36:57.520 --> 00:37:02.719
They have experience managing teams, but they're not setting the strategic direction.

00:37:02.719 --> 00:37:09.679
The head of AI, to me, is a person that manages teams. They're understanding how to position AI,

00:37:09.679 --> 00:37:15.040
the technology within the business, developing relationships with the stakeholders,

00:37:15.919 --> 00:37:19.120
kind of having higher oversight on the products that the teams are building.

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:24.800
So, I think of like a principal to be like a senior manager AD role. Head of AI is like a

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:32.479
senior director, you know, VP type of role. Awesome. Thank you. It's a great question,

