Jay, for joining us today. So, a quick question, and a little bit of context before I ask it. I'm

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:11.600
asking about kind of broadly speaking drawbacks and benefits of AI and in two different domains.

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:18.560
So, my question is, what are some of the types of work that Gen AI has helped with? And if any,

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:22.399
what are some of the drawbacks that you found? We've mentioned hallucinations here, for example,

00:38:23.040 --> 00:38:29.600
as one of the things. And if you could also talk about it both from a kind of like broad data

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:35.040
science perspective and as someone who's worked specifically in the domain of the biological

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:39.280
sciences. My experience is primarily social science, so I'm curious about maybe some of

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:48.800
the differences. Okay. Don't know how much I can say about that last one, but I'll definitely

00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:56.639
try to answer the first two. So, where is the type of work Gen AI has helped in this? So,

00:38:56.639 --> 00:39:02.959
let me give you a very kind of stupidly simple example. So, in our organization, we use safe

00:39:02.959 --> 00:39:09.679
agile. So, safe agile is agile, but with more meetings. And so, what you do is you have to write

00:39:09.679 --> 00:39:13.919
user stories and stuff like that. And it's very formal with how things are written. And you can

00:39:13.919 --> 00:39:19.360
imagine nobody likes that. No one writes the stories correctly. It's always a pain. It's always

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:25.120
a struggle. You always get yelled at because you don't write them properly. Now, one opportunity

00:39:25.120 --> 00:39:31.040
with Gen AI was what if we built a tool, a Shiny app, a Streamlit app, something that can connect

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:36.399
to where the stories are, and it can just rewrite them the proper way. And you literally just have

00:39:36.399 --> 00:39:40.159
someone that connects to it, rewrites it, you check it, and you click the button, and it's

00:39:40.159 --> 00:39:46.159
updated. There's nothing there. Like that's not a complicated solution, but it added a lot of value

00:39:46.159 --> 00:39:51.040
because it kind of automated the thing that people just don't like, they didn't want to do. And I

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:57.120
think that there's a lot of opportunities like that in every company. It's not just unique to

00:39:57.120 --> 00:40:05.679
Pharma. So, anything where you're reading text and having to extract information or process it,

00:40:05.679 --> 00:40:13.120
or to me, that is the richest domain of these tools. So, this is actually disproportionately

00:40:13.120 --> 00:40:16.959
things like corporate functions. You think of people that look at contracts all day.

00:40:16.959 --> 00:40:23.840
Think of people that have to write a lot, medical writers. So, I think that there's a lot of

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:29.919
writing, reading stuff, which is a huge domain here that becomes available with the technology.

00:40:31.120 --> 00:40:40.000
I think the drawbacks of it are there's a learning curve to using it.

00:40:40.959 --> 00:40:49.919
So, when I build a solution, I've said this from the beginning, the distance between failure and

00:40:49.919 --> 00:40:57.199
success is very, very thin. It actually is pretty hard to get a solution that works well and is

00:40:57.199 --> 00:41:03.760
robust. You may fail nine times, and then somehow with some little tweak of something, it just

