00:48:08.719 --> 00:48:10.479
that's a really, really important one.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:17.360
This is an open question, and it actually is related to grift.

00:48:18.320 --> 00:48:23.919
The way I look at this is, I have a team that's focused on delivery. We have access to all the

00:48:23.919 --> 00:48:29.439
same tools that every other vendor has in the universe, right? Like, it's not like some SaaS

00:48:29.439 --> 00:48:35.919
company, S-A-A-S, not S-A-S, some SaaS company has some magical access to models that we don't have.

00:48:35.919 --> 00:48:42.399
We're all starting from the same level. So, my thing is, okay, if I see a technology,

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:48.159
we know the technology is very, very powerful. What is the vendor bringing to the table? Are

00:48:48.159 --> 00:48:55.600
they bringing intellectual property or expertise or something like a more mature product that is

00:48:55.600 --> 00:49:02.080
truly differentiated from Jay slapping a wrapper and a streamlined app together to solve a problem?

00:49:02.080 --> 00:49:07.439
And that's really where, that's my anchoring is, if I had to build this in a streamlined app in

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:14.639
three weeks, how much better is what I'm seeing than that? And as you start to interrogate what

00:49:14.639 --> 00:49:21.439
the tool does, in many cases, it falls down. Like, a lot of times the solution is a React front end

00:49:22.080 --> 00:49:29.520
